Vaccination against pneumococcal bacteria will be free and voluntary
Vaccination against the increasing the old habits as early as january.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Voices already, saying that a compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against increasing riots.
The pharmaceutical institute for vaccines already defines the maximum prices that will pay for health insurance.
Specialists are also clear in the process of vaccination.
A new vaccination. "
Free vaccines for children in August.
Since january, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated against pneumocoques.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If we began vaccination last year or earlier, we will have to pay yourself vaccination.
The first dose of vaccine should be administered between the third and the fifth month of the child.
Last year a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated children against the pneumocoques.
Yet parents paid 1,600 crowns or more for a dose.
The vaccination of younger requires four doses.
Experts estimate that each year the health insurance spend 300 to 450 million kronor in doses of vaccine.
However, they save on medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
So far the state spent approximately 500,000 kronor per year for the vaccination of children.
Vaccination repaid was introduced with the "Janota package.".
Pneumococcal bacteria are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also of serious infections including the inflammation of the brain and blood poisoning.
According to surveys in hospitals, there has until 28 deaths of children under 10 years caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced vaccination repaid.
Vaccination will be mandatory?
There are opinions regarding a possible mandatory vaccination in the future.
From January, it must be resolved by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that a compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted vaccination against pneumococcal bacteria.
At an international conference in which our association participated, experts were not really satisfied with the fact that we have a voluntary vaccination.
This is not ideal. "
On the other hand, we are pleased to have been able to impose at least.
I think it is a direction that we must now follow said Kalovský.
But the Ministry of Health does not change the process of vaccination against pneumococcal bacteria.
We do not for the moment, "said his spokesman Vlastimil sršeň.
The voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, say doctors. "
Hana Cabrnochová, President of the Society of pediatricians, recognizes that a vaccine based on the volontariata its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, it could consider a reduction of renewals of vaccinations "In the situation where the vaccine is such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional" said however Cabrnochová.
Experts predict that by next year, more than 80 per cent of new parents will vaccinate their infants.
Vaccination against pneumocoques marks a break from the fact that this is the first vaccination of children which is financed by the insurance and not the state.
Cabrnochová explained that insurance should free up funds for prevention, they would save and on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves.
This is linked to the concerns of practitioners, related to the purchase of vaccines.
The original intent was to buy vaccines by insurance, doctors receiving the same way as other products of vaccine provided by the state.
Some Members were concerned, however, that this would allow insurance companies to deduct the amount of health insurance. "
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for the insurance.
According to estimates, pediatricians individually invest nearly 40 000 SEK per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová. "
