The results of the tests reveal persistent differences between races.
The federal report last week on the results in mathematics has brought good news for public schools in Washington D.C.
Although the District is still far behind the lead institutions, the report shows that the Grade 4 and Grade 5 (cm1-cm2) are much greater progress in the past two years than in cities such as Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what is clear from the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (National Assessment of Educational Progress) is the persistent gap between the results of African-Americans and whites, on both local and National level.
The results means of white children in Grade 4 (CM1) to WashingtonD.C. have increased over the past two years, 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500), but those of their classmates African-American increased by only three points, 209 to 212.
The gap of success has actually increased between 2007 and 2009, from 53 to 58 points.
The progress of African-Americans in Grade 8 (4th) generally remains constant, falling only one point, from 245 to 244.
The result means of whites has not been included in the results of the tests because the sample was not enough.
The overview over a period of six years is not more encouraging.
In 2003, the gap between blacks and whites in Grade 4 (), when the first report was published, the District was 60 points (262 to 202).
Although the results achieved by children in both groups have increased during this period, the difference was only reduced to 58 points.
Last week, some advocates in the District have expressed concern that rising celebrated by the Director of group of educational institutions Michelle A. Rhee and Mayor Adrian M. Fenty (Democrat) were propelled by the white students who were already good elements.
This would mean that we have raised the aggregate in considering the elements at the top of the scale, which is problematic and embarrassing, said Jeff Smith, Director of DC Voice, a non-profit group that promotes equality in education in the District.
I do not jump for joy for one or two points earned, "said Kwame R. Brown (related Democrat), Member of the Council of D.C. and whose daughter is in Grade 4, Eaton Elementary (elementary school).
Often critical of the management style of Rhee, Brown said that the message of the results of tests is that the middle schools (colleges) of the city desperately need attention.
Really, you always see the positive signs and I respect that.
But fear is that we do not spend enough time and energy to our middle schools (colleges).
Rhee said the District should continue to find better ways to meet the needs of students in difficulty.
This fall, for example, some teachers have been trained to use a new method of reading, the Wilson Reading System, for classes end of elementary school and early college who not have integrated the Reading earlier in their school and who are behind their peers.
Each day, the Mathematics curriculum for grades Kindergarten (kindergarten to Grade 6 (6th) focuses on the games and real life experiences, as they have been put in place in the District by the former superintendent Clifford Janey, which must also be credited for the progress of the NAEP reported last week.
I simply believe that we must continue to work to provide better services to these students below the level of the class, said Rhee.
Others believe that the results of the NAEP raise the question of whether Rhee can continue to raise the overall results of the system while providing money and resources for schools with less good results in order to reduce the gap.
It is a dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a trainer of education at the University of California at Berkeley who is studying the results of the tests of cities.
The conventional political solution is to spend your resources and management reforms to schools in the poorest neighborhoods of Washington.
Also this targeting may have political repercussions this important program.
But the problem, of course, is that as the other Superintendant schools, it is trying to use the middle class whites and blacks.
We focus to ensure the development of a system of good schools.
We must strengthen our neighbourhood schools so that all families, regardless of where they come from, be assured that their children will be able to obtain an excellent public education.
Janey, now Superintendent of Schools of Newark, said in an interview this week, that one of the essential elements to reduce the gap of success is traditional public school time, now 180 days in the District of Washington, to be in competition with the Charter schools.
It takes approximately 200 days to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with the union of its teachers last year for 185 days, that it considers a "starting point" for an increase in the next contract.
To make higher education a promise for the future
The bus stopped in Gettysburg College with a long whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12 years, falls and blinks an eye at the sight of white columns, facades of bricks and rolling lawns.
The parents of Graciela had only been able to complete high school, àEl Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela itself, who was born in Silver Spring and lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a university campus.
Also, when she and other students in Grade 8 (4th) of the group explored Gettysburg where tuition fees are $38 690 per year, his attitude was less a new student impressed that enthusiastic.
Super This is where I'll study! exclaimed Graciela wishing to study medicine, while the guide the heading toward the entrance of the building of science.
Youpi, really? "She says pensive, when he said the low ratio law professor - student.
The University of Pennsylvania was The seventh that were visiting children during their journey of discovery of three days and now they had completely integrated The message: The question is not whether you go to University:
The question is where. "
Although this question is still largely for the large number of American children born to parents Hispanic migrants who have left the school where became parents to adolescence, they are also hundreds of thousands to benefit from university education that will allow them to enter the middle class.
In fact, a "Hispanic" second generation "on cinqpoursuit his studies at the school -- a notable achievement considering that so many of their immigrant parents, most from Mexico or Central America, came to the United States without having completed high school.
Their success is important, say researchers, they pave the way for future generations who will play an important role in the workforce of the country.
Researchers studying the wings say that they have a natural affinity with the school and an innate need to succeed.
Many are also those whose parents set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
The mentoring programs also play a very important role in helping Graciela and millions of children as it to reach the university -- in particular, if its efforts are regular and long-term.
When you look at the children of low-income families with parents who do not have the experience and skills to help them navigate the system, any intervention, at any time, will not help, said Patricia Gándara, a researcher at Davis, University of California, who has studied Latin American students.
We need to provide a support network for these children, from kindergarten to high school.
The federal program which funded the visit of Graciela is a good example.
Known as the GEAR UP (prépares you), it provides more than $300 million per year to local school systems to organize the university preparation programs that begin when students from low income families are in middle school (college) and continue until the end of years of high school.
Since 1999, the program has been followed by more than 10 million students, with more than 60 percent entering university, according to the US Department of Education.
The Department of Iraqi oil has agreements with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has managed to attract major oil companies to rebuild its infrastructure in difficulty during two auction that ended Saturday.
The 10 agreements reached by the Ministry of Iraqi Oil with foreign Oil companies suggest that the Oil companies from china, Russia and Europe are poised to play a major role in the rehabilitation of the Oil industry of iraq, invalidated by decades of war and sanctions.
American companies are left with an interest in only two of the 10 fields auctioned.
Seven US companies had paid to attend the second auction that began Friday.
The only one that had set an auction has lost.
Two American companies have obtained contracts for the fields auctioned in June.
The low representation of American oil giants in the opening of the oil sector in Iraq has surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors, after six years of war, and instead of American companies are of Asian and European companies that are leading the way, "said Ruba husari, editor of the forum Iraq Oil forum, a site of information on the internet.
It will take a long time before another offer is made in Iraq.
The concerns about security, corroborated by massive coordinated bombings Tuesday, and political instability, while the U.S. military troops withdraw U.S. oil companies have slowed, preventing them from entering with greater force in Iraq, which has the third largest oil reserve in the world, say analysts.
American companies were, in some cases, disadvantaged because of their rivals, especially the Chinese and other energy companies controlled by a government, including labour costs were significantly lower and who were more willing to take risks because they had not accountable to shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies to obtain contracts with the department.
The most important American companies such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which have maintained strong links with the Iraqi Ministry of Oil and brought their technical advice, are left empty-handed.
The Russian company Lukoil and Gazprom were the two main shareholders in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The Chinese National Petroleum Corp., owned by the State, has more enchéri on contracts that other companies and left with substantial ownership in contracts for two main fields.
We all know that China is becoming a major economy, as well as a technological power, said Assam Jihad, spokesman of the Ministry of Oil.
We are confident that Chinese society will be on an equal footing with its competitors and achieve its commitments in Iraq.
The companies to submit auctions have made offers, which were then compared to the price per barrel that the department agreed to pay to motivate the production above current levels for each field.
