It seems that an American missile, which hit along the border with Afghanistan has killed one of the organizers of the operations of Al-Qaida, this week, said Friday the US authorities of counter-intelligence.
If the information is confirmed, it would be the second deadly attack against a terrorist leaders this fall.
Saleh al-Somali was one of two Arab men suspected to have been killed by a pair of missiles launched in their car, Tuesday, near the town of Miran shah, in the province of North waziristan, according to us sources and Pakistani authorities in the region.
Local authorities have said that the missiles had been fired by a pilotless aircraft of the type used by the CIA, in the tribal border of Pakistan.
They were driving a white car, moving towards the Afghan border, when the car was hit, said a member of the secret services Pakistani civilians, speaking by telephone from Miran Shah.
The representatives of the authority said that local militant suspects rushed to place and quickly confiscated what remained of "body completely.
It was completely impossible to local authorities to verify the identity of the victims, but the two American counterterrorism officials have yielded unspecified evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali was described as one of the main military organizers who ran the al-Qaeda terrorist operations group outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
Its role was to organize conspiracies around the world, "said one of the authorities who wished to remain anonymous, citing the sensitive nature of air strikes inside Pakistani territory.
Given its central role, this was probably the conspiracies of attacks against the United States and Europe.
It followed the strategic leaders of al-qaeda and has translated into action plans for possible terrorist attacks.
A second representative of the American authority said that Somali had increased rapidly in the ranks of al-Qaida' s and had very good relations with other extremist groups in the region.
It is perhaps not known to the general public, but this does not diminish the threat it poses for us and our allies, "said the second official representative.
