The UN special envoy in afghanistan, Kai eide, said Friday that he would resign from his post in march, at the end of a tumultuous tenure marred by allegations of corruption extended during the presidential elections supported by the United nations.
The departure of Eide comes at a time when the Obama administration decided to send 30,000 additional troops in Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said he supported this increase, but he expressed his concern about the US timetable for a withdrawal of troops that would begin in 18 months and other governments of NATO to withdraw their forces.
We need to accelerate the development of our security forces in Afghanistan, send the right signal to Afghans and remind them that they can have confidence in the international community, "said Eide in a telephone interview from Kabul.
Our commitment must be long-term. "
The Norwegian diplomat has also urged the us and other military powers to increase the number of international staff assisting the political transition in afghanistan.
The increase must be copied by civilians, he said.
Eide said he did not resign but that it would respect the commitment he had made to his family, in march, will spend two years in kabul.
He said he wanted to prevent the United Nations. "
The Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon now knows that he has time to find a replacement.
I simply said that it was better to start looking for my replacement, Eide said.
When I came here, there was a gap of two months between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival.
According to the representatives of the United Nations, Ban has already begun to seek a replacement.
