USA: a sign of sarcophagus that belonged to Zola awarded 1.5 million USD
A panel of Roman sarcophagus belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was awarded Thursday 1.5 million, well above its estimate, announced the art dealer Sotheby's.
This sign before two metres long on 63 cm high, dating from the third century A.D., was estimated at between 150,000 and 250,000 dollars.
The marble "representing four other scenes in a sophisticated architectural decoration, surrounded by satyres and bacchantes, is a rare piece, there are only four or five in the world," explained to AFP Tuesday Florent Heintz, vice-president of the auction of art of the Roman and Egyptian antiquities in Sotheby's.
It was sold in $lots.
The sale is still ongoing but this lot is certainly one on which buyers have the most outbidding so far, told AFP a spokesman for Sotheby, Dan Abernethy.
The discovery of the acquisition of the marble by Emile Zola back in a few days.
The sign remained nearly 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the Borghese family, then became successively among French actress Cécile Sorel, who had been an element of his bathtub in his mansion in Paris, and Paul Reynaud, Minister under the Third Republic in France and briefly president of the Council before the accession to power of Marshal Pétain.
A grey area of about 50 years.
In searching the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz discovered that this sign was part of a "succession Emile Zola" opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and the epic "Rougon-Macquart".
