Mexico has seen Thursday that the conditions were not right for the transfer on its territory of the deposed president of Honduras, Manuel Zelaya, who was denied a safe conduct by the government.
For the moment, after a telephone conversation in the night with President Zelaya, everything seems to indicate that the feasibility of this transfer are not met, said the Mexican Foreign Minister Patricia Espinosa.
Arrived Wednesday in El Salvador to bring Mr Zelaya, the Mexican government plane returned to its place of origin, according to a source of the General Directorate of Migration.
The government wanted to force Mr Zelaya to "resign" and to seek political asylum abroad to give him a safe conduct.
But the president refused, because he wanted to visit Mexico as a sitting head of state invited.
The coup government "has been another failure in that I renounced my office (...), they wanted me to resign," said Thursday, Mr Zelaya radio Globo, on which it is often since the beginning of the political crisis that has lasted for five months in the countries of Central America.
I can stay here ten years here I have my guitar, added by playing a few agreements the deposed president, refuge at the Brazilian embassy in Tegucigalpa for two and a half months.
The Embassy of Mexico has submitted a request for safe conduct, but unfortunately we cannot accept this because it does not include a request for asylum, said Wednesday the Minister of Interior of the rebel government, Oscar Raul Matute, radio HRN Honduran.
I do not request asylum in any country, said Manuel Zelaya in an interview with the Qatar-based Telesur, headquartered in Caracas.
A possible departure of Honduras will do as president of the Honduran people, he said.
Rumours of departure of Mr Zelaya had mobilized Wednesday, supporters of the deposed president, who came to unite around the embassy of Brazil, where the military have strengthened their seat.
The Brazilian Foreign minister, Celso Amorim, has criticised the government's position.
This demonstrates the marginal nature of this government to international standards, he said.
Zelaya, who was closer to the socialist president Hugo Chavez, was ousted on June 28, the day he had organized a popular consultation to prepare his re-election, against the advice of the Supreme Court, military and Congress.
Exile in Costa Rica, he had returned by surprise on 21 September and had taken refuge in the Brazilian embassy.
If he leaves, he will be arrested for the offence of "high treason" accuses the ex-paratrooper justice, according to the government.
The president Roberto Micheletti has managed to hold a presidential election on 29 November to replace Mr Zelaya.
Porfirio Lobo was elected during the controversial recognized by the United States but disputed by Latin American countries such as Venezuela, Argentina or Brazil.
Three days later, Congress voted overwhelmingly against the return of Mr Zelaya to power until the end of its mandate on January 27.
