Road: three marathons for an agreement that saves the supply of Christmas
After three sessions of marathon talks, the road sector unions and employers' organisation TLF, only to be stayed until the end, arrived Friday evening in an agreement that puts an end to the strike and the threat to the supply of Christmas.
At the meeting of signatures Friday evening, the secretary of state for transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "delighted" of this agreement, after several rounds of negotiations, which began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions the negotiators were left in the early morning Friday, with the hope of signing quickly in late morning the text of the agreement.
Even if three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it took more than six hours of the meeting started at 11.00 for everyone agrees that the text should be signed.
The conflict "would have been very damaging for business" and "it was feared that it will disrupt the holidays for years," said Mr Bussereau.
The text provides for a wage increase of 4% for the lowest wages (in the local and regional road transport), and 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
In hourly rate, for the bas-salaires, "8,72 to 9,06.
It is not much, but it is very far, "said Patrice Clos (FO).
This is going to give the order to our activists that there is no, no amount of supplies.
But we can always have a few holdouts who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, welcomed "a good agreement", even if it was "difficult to concede the increases on the senior salaries because of international competition."
According to him, the increases will be of the order of 170 euros a month for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is the agreement of common sense and respect of employees, "said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) has hailed a" historic agreement ".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) has referred to "an acceptable compromise.".
The agreement also provides for the upgrading of the travel expenses of 3%, and the holding of general state of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will address the issue of a 13th month and modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "a decrease of EUR 100 million in employers' contributions" was the subject of a Government amendment to the bill amending finance for 2009, voted in Thursday night on Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "in".
The signing of TLF allows the Agreement applies initially to companies adhering to this organization, and in a second time, the entire profession, in case of an extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be "as soon as possible," said Mr Bussereau.
The opposition of employers' organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "fool" because the EUR 100 million "had already been promised to the sector to offset a portion of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport has obliged us to negotiate in L? urgency, not a shared analysis, but not to thwart the eaters of the next, deplored the Unostra.
For the otre, the agreement risk "digging the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
