The Turkish Justice dissolved the pro-Kurdish party, decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled Friday the dissolution of the main pro-Kurdish party in the country, a decision that was immediately followed by expressions of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-east of the country and Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is to reach out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "hotbed of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said to the press, the president of the court Hasim Kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously of 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, said Mr Kiliç, adding that 37 cadres of the party, including its chairman Ahmet Turk and Aysel Tugluk MP, are banned from politics for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and confiscation by the Treasury assets of the party.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that Members would leave Parliament rather than sit as parliamentarians without a label.
The decision follows a process launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP to obey "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers Party (pkk), considered a terrorist organisation by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political wing of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, that there was "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with him.
The verdict of the Court comes at a time when the government has to reach out to the Kurdish community in proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, to try to shrink the support of Kurds and put an end to the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP had said that a dissolution could lead to an escalation of tensions in the southeast Anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP in Diyarbakir, the largest city in southeastern populated mainly by Kurds.
The security forces fired tear gas and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails and stones, with fronds.
About 100 people attended the rally in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the decision of Justice would "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish, Editor's note) by prohibiting a party, he said to the Press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This does not resolve, "said Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total of democratic openness launched by the government, "said the political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction of the PKK, he added.
Thursday, the PKK has claimed an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in the north of Turkey, one of the most deadly in recent months.
The new "silicon valley"
For a long time she had the reputation of city secret, banned visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the 10 districts of Moscow, was under the Soviet regime, a place of secret weapons, under strict supervision.
Today with its 216 000 inhabitants to 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the "Silicon Valley".
Centres of production and research into micro - and nanoelectronics are implanted.
As early as September 2008 representatives of Zelenograd have established links with Riedberg, place des Sciences Mehr – with academic institutions and companies of the centre of innovations in Frankfurt (FIZ).
There have been meetings reciprocal and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg signed a "Memorandum of close collaboration".
The signatories were the Deputy Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz Section Chief project for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will depart at Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific Exchange
It is a scientific exchange.
But also of economic relations. "
It will enable the companies to enter the Russian market in full expansion.
Has the opposite the Russian scientists want to obtain contracts in germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of research institutes and companies Soviet famous.
There is the Institute of Electrical Engineering from Moscow, the big firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The policy was founded in 1958 as "socialist planned city" for research.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") gets its name from the wooded hills in the heart of which research centres are located.
The project S21: a brake for Stuttgart, Germany
Cannot be placed high enough the magnitude of the project Stuttgart 21.
To its supporters it is nothing less than "new heart of Europe".
If. Is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a massive construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg, in a hopeless chaos of for 10 years.
Stuttgart 21 is born of the spirit of the 1980s.
The stations, with tracks which ended in town, had a reputation at the time of the relics of the technique of transport of the 19th century that were effect of brake shoe modern rail traffic because it was once a lot of time to get the locomotives from the back to the front.
Arrival, stopping short, start - that is what needs to be done.
That is why the stations to disappear: In Frankfurt and Munich.
And stuttgart also: a station of trains, which lies halfway around on the construction Transeuropéenne rail between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava where the slogan "heart of europe".
The project S21 will really start, although the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners have recognized that the cost to bury the station in the capitals of Hesse and Bavaria, was exorbitant.
Indeed, the head of line stations no longer pose real problems of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with railcars and voiture-pilote at both ends.
However, it is now launching the achievement of Stuttgart 21 alongside the new line towards Inter-City Ulm.
The regional and communal prevailed.
The railway company is in part because it is the taxpayer who paid the cost of the largest infrastructure project of the federal republic and not the public company.
From the point of view of this project is relatively well justified.
You get an urban space which according to the planners generated by computer will be very.
For the system of rail transport the S21 is at fault.
The station and enlargement of the section are designed for the trafficking of people which was - and this is typical of the 1980s - an enormous growth.
At the time there was no competition from cheap flights.
The policy of modern traffic should first concentrate on strengthening the traffic of goods transport by rail is much more environmentally friendly than by truck on the road.
But the new route, with its inclinations, not suitable for freight trains.
The s21, and this is much more serious indirectly affects many other rail projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the Swabian.
It is the official figure. "
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion are more realistic.
One thing is for sure, in the next decade will this money for other nodes and congestion in the network.
The list of the Ministry of Transport in 60 major projects.
One of the most important is the enlargement of the section across the Rhine Valley 180 kilometres.
Since 1987 the line is built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent support here to build on the fungus.
But the project is a braking.
The route of the Rhine Valley is becoming the bottleneck international freight traffic, and this in the heart of Europe.
