Brazil sets a date for the departure of Zelaya
The Brazilian government has set a deadline for the stay of Manuel Zelaya in its embassy in Tegucigalpa.
The deposed president will abandon the diplomatic legation no later than January 27, 2010, the date of the official end of its mandate.
Francisco Catunda, business for the Brazilian embassy in the capital of Honduras, confirmed to TV Globo that "Mel" knows that he must leave the embassy, where he is refugee since September 21, before that date.
"It is aware that he must leave on 27 January, at the end of its mandate, it must seek another destination."
The chain has also cited the former agent, who confirmed his intention to leave the embassy before the end of the deadline: "my position is to leave as soon as possible, with the support of the Brazilian government," Zelaya said by telephone.
After the elections of 29 November (during which Porfirio Lobo was elected), Zelaya said he would remain in the Embassy of Brazil until January.
However, the same week, he tried to seek refuge in Brazil.
The operation ultimately failed, since Zelaya refused the condition of exiled policy that would impose the de facto government headed by Roberto Micheletti.
Thank you very much.
After days roses since last spring, during which asset inflation was the dominant note on the markets, the uncertainty there arises again, which is not surprising since it is their natural state, in an environment where officers take decisions on a future uncertain in nature.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilise the markets has been to monetize the debt by the direct purchase of assets and indirectly providing ample liquidity at rates close to zero, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilize.
Central banks have already confirmed that the direct purchases of assets were virtually finalised, and without questioning their political maverick of liquidity, begin to put a bit of sand in the wheels, as did the ECB, with their award to a year next week.
Therefore, investors have doubts about the ability of the global economy to maintain an economic recovery without heterodox measures and we are seeing a reversal of the reduction of risk premiums.
The volatility of scholarships and the corporate bond spreads rise again, although they remain very distant paranormaux levels that they have achieved at the beginning of the year.
States were forced to socialize the risk private and public debt is again affected.
There is a flight to quality and the United States, Japan and Germany have been selected shelters by investors, an increase of differences between the countries of the euro zone and Germany.
Spain has been barely affected by this episode of instability, but then Standard & Poor its threatened a new downward revision of the qualification of the Kingdom of Spain.
On the other hand, a bit of uncertainty is not bad to silence the defenders of moral hazard, who tried to provoke a new case of conscience in understanding of global economic policy that had hampered the destructive effects of limiting the credit derivatives on the destruction of employment, whereas what should be done is to impose a new Thanksgiving.
However, the situation of Dubai resembles a fight between the tribal sheiks to restore power in the emirates and we have already seen the case of greece.
A government that conceals a public deficit, elections, and a new government who discovers the ruse.
Prodi did in Italy after Berlusconi and Socrates in Portugal after Durão Barroso.
It would be perfectly irrational that Ecofin saves Hungary a breach of its external payments at the beginning of the year and allow a member country of the euro area not to meet its commitments.
What makes sense is that the Ecofin has prompted the Greek government transparency and makes its citizens share the need for extraordinary measures to maintain the stability of its public finances.
If, as we hope, we are faced with an episode of normalization of risk premiums, after some excesses in high positions, it would be predictable.
In the case of spain, as our differences of public debt is increasing to the extent of the obligations of European companies, nousn not to worry.
If the European and continued to increase, it would be a risk idiosyncratic Spanish.
The Standard & poor's is an anecdote. When our indicators forecast forced most of the services of studies to anticipate their models of recovery and to revise up their forecasts for 2011, with the OECD and the European commission, returning to the burden with a Japanese model pourl Spanish economy, it does not much hope for their warning.
Again, this has all the air to provide an excellent opportunity to buy assets Spanish, even if for the moment "caution is the mother safety."
Sectors connected to
The chairman of Iberdrola, Ignacio Sánchez Galán, was the first to intervene yesterday, before the subcommittee of the Congress of Deputies, which is discussed these days the energy strategy of Spain for the next two decades.
After his speech, which was followed by the President of Gas Natural-Fenosa, Rafael Villaseca, Mr Galán has outlined for the press what he had told the subcommittee, in camera.
For the president of Iberdrola, Spain needs to invest 50 000 million until 2020 and 60 000 million more between that date and 2030, where the nuclear power plants in operation would remain open.
If this is not the case, the necessary investments do not amount to 60,000 million but to 95,000.
By contrast, Iberdola considers that for the next decade, investments should not be used to increase production capacity, but the distribution networks and international interconnections.
From 2020, the question is changing, and it will increase the power.
His bet focuses both gas and coal, with mechanisms for recovery of carbon dioxide and, above all, on renewable energy.
In this area, it considers that 18,000 MW of more are needed, with other energies "support".
Galán, who believes that the draft Law a sustainable economy that the government has just approved is in line with what his company, did not want to attack the royal decree aimed to encourage the use of coal, which contradicts the policies to combat global warming.
According to him, there was "a clear long-term bet" in this sense, despite the measures "one-off" as described the chairman of Iberdrola.
Anyway, Galán believes that decisions to invest, although they are in the long term, must begin to be taken, because they take some time before reaching maturity and a lucrative stable framework is needed to address them.
